content.description:
On the east face of Layback Rock is a scooped out line of hard holds.  

  I showed this once upon a time project to Eric in 1998, and told him it was undone. In no time flat the  flames were lit, and he fired it off in a handful of tries. I was never able to do it, so it could be harder than V8. I think I was too tall;) 

  Eric's been climbing for forty years or more, whith much of that time traveling and sampling the goods all over the country. Classic, hard problems tend to bob around in his wake, and I think this line is another to add to the list. At 54, he's still capable of bouldering V8's and harder when he's in shape. a true inspiration.
This one seems straight out of Bishop: climb the lovely left-facing flake and patina to a committing long reach over the lip. Top out on super cool square inclusions. One of Groom's finest highballs.
content.protection: A couple pads and friends. There is potential for a dangerous fall to the left.
content.location: On the Lieback Rock, head left around the corner from The Infamous Lieback; look for the tall left-facing rail just past a wide crack.

content.description: Tons 'a fun. Start hugging the rock and follow the right edge of the scoop.
content.protection: A pad or two and a spot, it is good not to fall when you are topping out.
content.location: Just above Bolt Rock on an adjacent boulder, this climbs an obvious arete feature right of a scoop.

content.description: Often ignored, this striking line sees few repeats. Starting with a right side pull, move onto arête and continue up very technical climbing to the top of this stunning feature.
content.protection: Kinda bad from what I remember. Lots of pads!
content.location: Sweeping arête left of Infamous Layback.

content.description: Head up the blank face between Space Lords and the obvious crack.  Start on the knob and enter the vertical realm of gastons and edges. A chicken head is waiting for you at the finish. Remember the aerets are off!
content.protection: Decent amount of pads (3 or 4) and good spotters
content.location: In-between Space Lords and the obvious huge crack.

content.description: The crack next to King Richard, super obvious. The top out for this climb can be exposed if you choose to follow the direct line up. There is a variation out right which is easier and less exposed. All and all, commitment/ confidence is key! Go big or go right on variation, your choice.
content.location: Layback rock, to the right of King Richard.

content.description: Easy laybacks to fingerlocks and a curious topout.
content.location: Just downhill from the Sucker Problem this is the obvious flake on the Lieback Rock.
On the same boulder as Slap problem. When looking at Infamous Lieback turn right and you should basically be able to see this problem.

content.description: Low start. Pull up and right to two obvious holds. Interesting mantle (crux) to high slab (kind of scary).
content.location: The canyon behind space lord. Climbs left of the detached boulder used to down climb formation.

content.description: Located on the U-Shaped feature directly across the canyon from the Fontainebleau/Scrotum boulder. This is two separate problems that I am counting as one. Not sure which is which, but one problem goes up left on the U to surmount the shelf and the other goes out right to accomplish the same goal. Both equally challenging, and like most groom creek routes, are friction dependent. Both routes start on the same crimp-jug. From here fire up to the textured sloping shelf and pick your direction. I personally find the left variation easier.
content.protection: Pads, spotters should help climber avoid smashing into the scrotum.
content.location: These problems are located on the U-Shaped feature of the large boulder directly across the canyon from the small, round, boulder (featuring Fontainebleau/The Scrotum) that is used in the decent from The Infamous Layback/Space Lord.

content.description: On the large, tall, Northeast face of Layback Rock is a beautiful, eye snagging layback seam. Climb that sucker to the scary top out. Sees very few ascents.
A prominent boulder next to the Back Porch. This area includes The Slapper Boulder.
